metadata.name: Antigravity #182
metadata.description:
To change size or quality, open the IPFS link in a separate window and append to its url a string like `&quality=400&tiles=9,16`. You may notice two parameters in it: `quality` and `tiles`.

`quality` is an integer from 1 to ~1000, the better the quality â€” the slower the rendering. Default is 200.

`tiles` is a number of 256Ã—256 px tiles to render. Can be an integer (for square images) or two integers separated with aÂ comma (for rectangular). `tiles=9,16` will make an image with width of 9Ã—256 px = 2304 px and height of 16Ã—256 px = 4096 px. If not set, adapts to screen size.

Press `s` to save the image.

metadata.name: an unrelated entity #51
metadata.description:
An experiment in maximal minimalism. The human brain's ability to deduce patterns and imagery given the the most basic input has always amazed me. Three circles and a handful of straight lines become a blazing sun and tall trees on a plain. 

I say "maximal" because this is far more code than I normally use; the "paper" alone is more code than my last three mints combined. The icons in the lower left are as follows: 

First icon: a binary representation of the transaction hash. 
Second icon: a meter denoting number of "trees"
Remaining icons: denote the boolean traits - sun, ring, and leaves.

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Nounfall #107
metadata.description:
Nounfall is drawn exclusively from the 234 heads and 21 glasses that are used to build the current Nouns collection. The background colors are all pulled from the blessed Noun palette.

This is ok because Nouns are CC0, which basically means public domain. Check out nouns.wtf for more info.

They make for fun social media banners when cropped, if you wanna show off you fandom of Nouns.

C : Clear screen and start animation over
S : Save current image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density to the respective number

So, if you want a high resolution file, tap `6` for it to redraw, and then `S` to save. You can also save while it's animating if you like, which is fun too.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #415
metadata.description:
â€œShapes on a Planeâ€ explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. Itâ€™s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

Iâ€™d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then iâ€™d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt Iâ€™d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: WTBS Logo with Friends #82
metadata.description:
Did you know that WTBS is now sixth months old? If we were Willâ€™s baby, weâ€™d be sitting up and prepping to crawl â€” the literal baby steps that precede an entire lifetime of movement. 

Play is another integral part of our development. Play teaches us to connect, laugh, share, love, and learn. It helps form our earliest friendships that mold us into who we are destined to become. Over the last six months we have had the immense pleasure of forming new relationships with some of the amazing artists that comprise of the fxhash community. 

It is the love and support of new friends Laurent Houdard, Ada Ada Ada, elsif, and Camille Roux that made our first (official) collaboration possible. Thank you so much for the idea, the vision, the art, the time, and the wrangling to make this possible. 

Each letter is imbued with the unique style of an artist, based on a framework created by Laurent. There is a small chance of receiving a piece with two of the same style, with the rarest possibility of receiving one with all four quadrants the same. 

Collect with love and the knowledge that your support means the world to us. Thank you for listening every week, and for the messages and stories that you share with us. We canâ€™t wait to continue to grow.

Thank you so much again to Laurent, Ada, elsif, and Camille. This is what community is.
